posts_info.description: THINGS TO KNOW FOR LONDON STADIUM CONCERT   People queued as early as 5am but most people came at 10am  Stand closest to the barricade facing the stadium  VIP is let in FIRST at 3:30pm then 45 mins later regular standing.  EVERYONE pushed, was worse inside!  Entrances open after 4:30pm so get water / food. MORE pushing.  Mike Dean comes on at 6pm followed by Kaytradana around 7pm  Abel came on at 8pm-ish and concert ended before 10:30pm  I stood close to the statue but he walks up and down the whole thing.  Buy some earplugs istg 😭 best decision ever.  Water is given regularly but you might need to fight for it.  ENJOY. These are now a Huge Staple within our Community. They had too take what they were given and had to noirish themselves with the food they were able too transform into meals and delicacy. But it wasn't just necessity that led Black Americans to identify with eating chitlins and these other dishes. Western Africans cooked and ate every edible part of animals, so they viewed entrails as more than scraps. These resourceful cooking techniques linger today, as Southerners continue to slow-cook or deep-fry these meals. #africanamericanhistory #soulfood #pigintestine #chitterlings #pig #discard #ancestors #ourhistory #truth #meals #southern #soulfood #africanamericanculture #africanamerican #africanamericanculture #cooking #soulaan #fyp

posts_info.description: Fine-dining customers were fooled into thinking they were eating at an exclusive #NewYorkCity restaurant called Mehran's Steakhouse. The elaborate prank was staged at an event space in #Manhattan.  The hoaxers went to amazing lengths to pull off the prank, including obtaining a one-day liquor license and food-handling permits. The kitchen was staffed by college kids who'd never worked in a restaurant before. Also, the "master chef" was a 21-year-old man who cooks for his friends. #MehransSteakhouse

A New Yorker, watching from an apartment across the street, cannot believe his eyes. From a distance, photographer @kieranknightley thinks he sees out-of-control flames inside a #Manhattan high-rise. After he called 911, firefighters rushed to the scene.  Turns out, those were not real flames. Instead, it was a #Yulelog fire video being played on a big TV screen in Ali Lyons' apartment.
Inside Edition is now streaming on Paramount+, and today we're bringing you a 24-hour true crime marathon.
Feeling stressed out and overwhelmed this holiday season? Take some time to zone out with #InsideEdition at the fireplace. Get cozy.

The #holiday season can leave many feeling sad and vulnerable, especially people who are experiencing grief.  Acclaimed best-selling writer and spiritual teacher #IyanlaVanzant’s daughter Gemmia died of cancer at just 31 years old. She understands how difficult the holiday season can be when someone you love is no longer there. Vanzant says to honor loved ones by doing “everything you know they loved,” and to shift out of “dysfunctional traditions.”

#Utah students are being hailed as heroes after helping lift a car pinning a mother and her son.  School officials say Bridgette Ponson and her two children were crossing the parking lot when they were accidentally hit by a driver who says she was blinded by the sun. Her daughter was able to crawl out but Ponson and her son were pinned under the vehicle. That’s when the students swarmed around the car to help.

In honor of the anniversary of John Lennon's death 43 years ago, we're sharing our New York Gritty on his last day in #NewYork.  On the evening of December 8, 1980, #JohnLennon and #YokoOno stepped out of a limousine by their apartment building. A man pulled out a gun and shot him in cold blood in the vestibule of the building. Police respond to the scene right away. When they saw the amount of blood coming from Lennon's body, they knew they could not wait for an ambulance.  They put him in the back of a police car and went directly to the hospital. They also arrested the shooter, #MarkDavidChapman.

Today marks the start of #Hanukkah, a Jewish holiday that lasts eight days. The ways it’s celebrated vary widely, Rabbi Menachem Creditor, Scholar-in-Residence at UJA-Federation of New York, told #InsideEdition.  “The way that we observe Hanukkah has a lot of diversity, depending on what kind of Jew you are or where in the world you find yourself, but one of the commonalities is that it's a tradition to light the candles and to place them facing the outside world,” he said.
